PARLIAMENT - Deputy president David Mabuza briefed leaders of political parties in parliament on the state of readiness for the memorial and funeral services of the late struggle stalwart Mama Winnie Madikizela Mandela at the Union Buildings in Pretoria. READ:Â Winnie was 'a torchbearer for freedom': Mabuza Following the news of Madikizela-Mandela's death, President Cyril Ramaphosa declared a Special Official Funeral Category 1 in line with Official and Provincial Official Funeral Policy. The funeral will have elements of military and ceremonial honours An inter-ministerial committee has been established to oversee the logistical arrangements of both events. The committee is led by the Minister in The Presidency, Dr Nkosazana Dlamini Zuma. The IMC comprises of all relevant stakeholders including the bereaved family of Madikizela-Mandela. Mabuza thanked leaders of political parties for their, "unwavering support and commitment to honour Mama Madikizela-Mandela and the conduct of various members of the public displayed at various memorial events taking place throughout the country." WATCH: Seipei's mother says she forgave Winnie long ago Dlamini-Zuma reported that government has since declared days of mourning from 3 April leading up to the funeral on Saturday, 14 April. Madikizela-Mandela will be laid to rest at the Fourways Memorial Park Cemetery. The deputy president will deliver the official address at the Official Memorial Service on Wednesday, 11 April at the Orlando Stadium in Soweto while president Cyril Ramaphosa will deliver the eulogy at the official funeral. Mabuza extended an invitation to all leaders of political parties to send Madikizela-Mandela off. eNCA